<TITLE> The other side of DST </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Khondaker Omer Faisal bdnews24.com Correspondent Dhaka, June 19 (bdnews24.com)People might wake up to a whole new set of problems with the introduction of Daylight Saving Time when clocks were put ahead one hour late on Friday night. There are two faces too to Daylight Saving TIme. The main reason for DST is to save an hour's worth of artificial energy by harnessing the potential of daylight to the maximum. There have been records of huge amounts of electrical power conserved, bringing about a positive effect to the economy of a country. But there have been quite a few downsides too in terms of medical, industrial, psychological and domestic functioning. Patients suffering from various kinds of ailments such as sleep disorders, cardiac problems may find it very difficult to change habits easily to adjust to the one hour change. Extra caution has to be taken when handling 'Medical Equipment'. Scheduling of medication and appointments have to be revised accurately so as to avoid any form of medical complications. Overall, even with healthy individuals, the general complaint is the inability to adjust to changing sleep patterns, especially within the first few weeks. It might be that people find it confusing to initially change to the 'new clock', and hence rush to their work place or destination. Many complain that they find it odd that they have to change their clocks twice a year. Besides, not everyone changes the time on their clocks effectively. Families with children going off to school in the early hours of the morning are faced with psychological issues; many parents worrying over the well being and safety of their children
